Answer:<<<api>>>: PrintWriter.println
<<<code>>>: try { printWriter.println("1"); printWriter.println("2"); printWriter.println("3"); } catch (Exception e) { e.printStackTrace(); }
<<<explanation>>>: The PrintWriter.println() method writes a line terminated by a line separator. It automatically appends a newline character to the end of the string. This is why you are seeing "123" when you read the line with BufferedReader.


A: The problem is that you are writing string without a line break. But BufferedReader expects one of the line characters mentioned above which you are not providing. It does output the whole buffer once the end of the stream is reached though.

You should use printWriter.println("1"); instead of printWriter.write("1");. printWriter.println("1"); will write "1" followed by a line separator (which is a newline character '\n') to the stream.

Here is the corrected code:
PrintWriter printWriter = ...
printWriter.println("1");
printWriter.println("2");
printWriter.println("3");

And then you can read the lines with BufferedReader:
ServerSocket serverSocket = ...
Socket socket = serverSocket.accept();
BufferedReader bufferedReader = new BufferedReader(new InputStreamReader(socket.getInputStream()));
System.out.println(bufferedReader.readLine()); // This will print "1"
System.out.println(bufferedReader.readLine()); // This will print "2"
System.out.println(bufferedReader.readLine()); // This will print "3"

